      Libor
   =20
 =20

At a high level, to be guilty of fraud, you need to (1) say something false=
 (2)=C2=A0know that it is false, or at least, have some sort of bad state o=
f mind about what you are saying. (Not legal advice and not quite right, bu=
t a good rough intuition.)=C2=A0When people get prosecuted for fraud, often=
 they will fight over both elements. =E2=80=9CEverything I said was more or=
 less true, but if it wasn=E2=80=99t then that was an honest mistake,=E2=80=
=9D they will say. But sometimes it is fairly obvious that what they said w=
as=C2=A0false, and so all of the arguments are over their state of mind: Wh=
en they said these untrue things, were they trying to trick people by knowi=
ngly lying, or was it forgivable carelessness?
It is rare, though, to have the opposite. It is rare for someone to be accu=
sed of fraud and say =E2=80=9Cwell yes obviously I intended=C2=A0to lie, bu=
t what I said was=C2=A0true, so it=E2=80=99s not fraud.=E2=80=9D It is not =
theoretically impossible, but it is weird. Usually when people try to lie t=
hey succeed, at least in the narrow sense of =E2=80=9Cthey try to say somet=
hing false and in fact say something false.=E2=80=9D On the rare occasions =
when they fail =E2=80=94=C2=A0when they try to lie and say something true i=
nstead =E2=80=94=C2=A0generally no one is tricked, and so there is no prose=
cution for fraud.
The state of fraud prosecutions for Libor, the London interbank offered rat=
e, is incredibly weird. Libor was a benchmark of banks=E2=80=99 borrowing c=
osts that was used to set rates on trillions of dollars of loans and deriva=
tives. The way it was set was that the administrator of Libor would call up=
 a bunch of banks every day and say =E2=80=9Chow much would you pay right n=
ow to borrow dollars for one month? Two months? Three months? What about ye=
n?=E2=80=9D and so forth, through a range of currencies and tenors. And the=
 banks would answer, and for each currency and tenor the administrator woul=
d throw out the extreme answers and average the rest, and that trimmed aver=
age would be two-month dollar Libor or whatever. And occasionally a bank wo=
uld get that call 30 seconds after it had negotiated to borrow dollars for =
one month, and its Libor submitter =E2=80=94=C2=A0the person who answered t=
he phone when the Libor administrator called =E2=80=94=C2=A0would confident=
ly say =E2=80=9Cour one-month dollar borrowing cost is 2.7539%,=E2=80=9D an=
d that was that. But most of the time the bank would not have taken out a t=
wo-month yen loan in the last hour, or the last day, or perhaps even the la=
st week, and it would have no directly observable answer to the question. S=
o it would estimate the answer. =E2=80=9CWe borrowed yen for one month yest=
erday at 0.25%, and since then rates seem to have moved by about 0.02%, and=
 the one-to-two-month curve is about 0.07%, so I=E2=80=99ll say 0.34%.=E2=
=80=9D And maybe that was actually the rate that the bank would have paid t=
o borrow yen for two months at the moment it answered the question, and may=
be it wasn=E2=80=99t.
These sorts of interpolations are not exactly rocket science, and the numbe=
rs the banks said were probably pretty close to what their actual borrowing=
 costs would be. But you could not say with much confidence that they were =
exactly right.
And then people at a bunch of banks got really into doing fraud on Libor. T=
he idea is that sometimes a derivatives trader=C2=A0had a billion dollars o=
f derivatives that were indexed to three-month dollar Libor, and if Libor w=
as 0.01% higher he would make an extra $100,000, and so he would call up hi=
s bank=E2=80=99s Libor submitter =E2=80=94=C2=A0and sometimes his buddies a=
t other banks =E2=80=94=C2=A0to try to nudge Libor higher. And the submitte=
r would be all ready to submit a Libor rate of 2.75%, and the trader would =
instant message him and say =E2=80=9Chelp me out I need it higher,=E2=80=9D=
 and the submitter would submit 2.76% instead.
And all of this would happen on permanently preserved electronic chats, and=
 all of the chats were=C2=A0as   bad as can  be. Basically the chats were l=
ike the traders saying =E2=80=9CI will pay you a bribe if you criminally ma=
nipulate Libor by lying in your submission,=E2=80=9D and the submitters say=
ing =E2=80=9Cokay I will do that because I am a dishonest liar, but I hope =
we do not get caught doing these blatant crimes,=E2=80=9D except with a lot=
 more misspellings. And so the banks got in trouble with regulators and qui=
ckly settled and paid billions of dollars of fines, and the individual trad=
ers who sent those chats were prosecuted for fraud.
Most famously, Tom Hayes, a former UBS Group AG derivatives trader, was pro=
secuted in the UK for manipulating Libor;   he sat for =E2=80=9C82 hours of=
 interviews with investigators=E2=80=9D in which he said things like =E2=80=
=9CI probably deserve to be sitting here because, you know, I made concerte=
d efforts to influence Libor,=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cultimately I was someon=
e who was a serial offender.=E2=80=9D Unsurprisingly, he was convicted.
He was also charged with crimes in the US, but now  those charges have been=
 thrown out:

A New York judge has thrown out criminal charges against Tom Hayes, the for=
mer UBS and Citigroup trader who served more than five years in prison in t=
he UK for conspiring to manipulate the Libor benchmark interest rate. ...
The decision to drop US charges against Hayes follows an appeals court ruli=
ng in a separate US case, which overturned the Libor-rigging convictions of=
 two former Deutsche Bank traders. That ruling found the government had =E2=
=80=9Cfailed to show that any of the trader-influenced submissions were fal=
se, fraudulent or misleading=E2=80=9D.

We   talked about that earlier ruling in January. The problem=C2=A0with the=
 Libor prosecutions=C2=A0is that nobody ever proved that the Libor submissi=
ons were wrong. Obviously the traders and submitters were=C2=A0trying=C2=A0=
to lie: The chats are terrible and show their state of mind pretty clearly,=
 and anyway Hayes spent hours confessing to manipulating Libor. But there i=
s no proof that they=C2=A0succeeded=C2=A0in lying: If a Libor submitter tho=
ught that his bank could borrow at 2.75%, and instead told the Libor admini=
strator that it could borrow at 2.76%, either number might have been right!=
 The appeals court pointed out that banks regularly borrowed different amou=
nts of money from different counterparties at different rates at around the=
 same time; it simply is not true that there was One Correct Rate that a ba=
nk would have paid to borrow money on any particular day. There is probably=
 some range, and if you pick a number in the range you are telling the trut=
h, even if you are consciously trying=C2=A0to pick the wrong number.
More to the point, it is very hard to=C2=A0prove=C2=A0that you are lying. I=
 mean, if you borrowed a lot of dollars for three months at 2.75% right bef=
ore the Libor administrators called, and then borrowed more at 2.75% right =
after, and you said =E2=80=9C2.76%=E2=80=9D when they called and asked for =
your three-month dollar borrowing rate, then that seems bad. But that is pr=
obably pretty rare, and ordinarily there will be some room for judgment. An=
d the burden of proof is on the prosecution: They need to prove that your L=
ibor submission was false, rather than you proving that it was true. That w=
ill generally be hard, and in any case US prosecutors never even tried. The=
y looked at all those chats, all those confessions of guilt, and figured th=
at they were good enough to prove that the traders were lying. But they nev=
er quite proved that they weren=E2=80=99t also telling the truth.

