<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Illiquidity provision</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One sort of financial innovation is about addi=
ng liquidity. There is some class of thing that does not trade very much fo=
r some reason, and you find a way to make it trade a lot. Perhaps the thing=
 is very big and not many people can afford to buy it, so you split it into=
 small pieces so people can trade the pieces. This basically describes the =
<em>stock market: </em>If you like Tesla Inc. as a company, you probably ca=
n=E2=80=99t go buy all of it, for a bunch of reasons of which the most impo=
rtant is that=C2=A0it costs $725 billion. But Tesla is split up into billio=
ns of shares, and you can go buy a share of Tesla for about $230.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or perhaps the things are very different and n=
on-fungible, making them hard to trade, so you smush lots of them into a bi=
g standardized package=C2=A0that is easier to trade. This is roughly the id=
ea behind mortgage bonds, or bond exchange-traded funds, or we <a href=3D"h=
ttps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29560330.279505/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3=
cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTAtMjYvbXVzay13aWxsLWJ1e=
S10d2l0dGVyLWF0LXRoZS1sYXN0LW1pbnV0ZT9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMTAxMjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1=
dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjExMDEmdXR=
tX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb8065845" itemprop=3D=
"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0000=
00; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bott=
om-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  t=
alked the other day</a> about a guy who wants to do it for diamonds. There =
is no visible trading=C2=A0market price for a 1.53-carat VVS1 diamond, beca=
use there aren=E2=80=99t that many diamonds with exactly those characterist=
ics, but if you can build some sort of standardized diamond basket then may=
be you can create a market price for that diamond, and thus a market.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Adding liquidity is, conventionally, desirable=
. It reduces risk: If you can sell a thing easily, that makes it less risky=
 to buy it, so you are more likely to commit capital to the thing. It incre=
ases demand: If only a few rich people can buy a thing with great difficult=
y, it will probably have a lower price than if everyone can buy a share of =
it easily. It improves transparency and makes prices more efficient. Also, =
financial innovation tends to be done by banks and other financial intermed=
iaries, and their goal is pretty much to do more intermediation. More liqui=
dity means more trading, which means more profits for banks.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another, funnier sort of financial innovation =
is about=C2=A0<em>subtracting=C2=A0</em>liquidity. If you can buy and sell =
something whenever you want at a clearly observable market price, that is <=
em>efficient</em>, sure, but it can also be <em>annoying</em>. Consider the=
 following financial product:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You give me the password to your brok=
erage account.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">I change it.</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You can=E2=80=99t look at your brokera=
ge account for one year, because you don=E2=80=99t have the password.</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">At the end of the year, I give you bac=
k your password and you pay me $5.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Is this a good product? For me, sure, I got $5=
 for like one minute of work.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-=
1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !impor=
tant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0For you, I would argue, it=E2=80=99s also pretty good. For one th=
ing, you avoid the stress of looking at your brokerage account all the time=
 and worrying when it goes down. For another thing, you avoid the popular t=
emptation of bad market timing: You can=E2=80=99t panic and sell stocks aft=
er they fall, or get greedy and buy more after they rise, because I have yo=
ur password. =E2=80=9CIt is well known that one of the best services a reta=
il broker can provide is not answering the phones during a crash,=E2=80=9D =
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29560330.279505/aH=
R0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjAtMDMtMDMvcm9ia=
W5ob29kLXBpY2tlZC1hLWJhZC1kYXktdG8tYnJlYWs_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTEwMTIyX01PTkVZU1RV=
RkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIxMTA=
xJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf9b36a3e" itempr=
op=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;=
">  I once wrote</a>; in this product I am charging you for that service. Y=
our mileage will vary =E2=80=94=C2=A0perhaps you are <em>good=C2=A0</em>at =
market timing =E2=80=94=C2=A0but=C2=A0this service might well be worth more=
 than $5 to you.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are variations. For instance, if you hav=
e borrowed money to buy a stock, and the stock=E2=80=99s market price drops=
 a lot, you will get a margin call from your broker asking you to put up mo=
re money. If you don=E2=80=99t have the money handy, the broker will sell t=
he stock, and you will have lost money. If the market price then recovers, =
you will regret it. If you could buy a service that was, like, =E2=80=9Cif =
the price of my stock falls by more than 10%, we shut down the stock market=
 and wait until the stock goes up again,=E2=80=9D then that would=C2=A0<em>=
probably=C2=A0</em>be useful to you.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#fo=
otnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border=
-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none=
 !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-bloc=
k;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0In general that is not a service that you can buy,<a class=3D"foo=
tnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration:=
 none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; b=
order-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !importa=
nt; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0but it is=C2=A0<em>kind of=C2=A0</em>a service that <em>some </em=
>people can buy. Xiang Guangda is a big metals tycoon, and he shorted a lot=
 of nickel on the London Metals Exchange, and the price of nickel went up a=
nd he had huge losses, and the London Metals Exchange shut down nickel trad=
ing for a week or so so that the price could go down and <a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29560330.279505/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxv=
b21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDctMDcvbmlja2VsLWJpZy1zaG90LWN=
hbGxlZC10aGUtc2hvdHM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTEwMTIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbW=
FpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIxMTAxJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb=
25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc5ee6bae" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" items=
cope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorati=
on: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000=
; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  he could avoid mos=
t of those losses</a>. That was a very helpful service that the LME provide=
d to him; they helped him out a lot, on his nickel trades, by shutting down=
 nickel trading.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or we have <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/29560330.279505/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vc=
GluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMTItMjAveW91LWQtcGF5LW5vdC10by1zZWUteW91ci1zdG9j=
ay1wcmljZT9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMTAxMjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9=
zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjExMDEmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1Zm=
Y/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB26a9cc22" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"it=
emscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  talked about</a> a fun post =
from Cliff Asness titled =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbus=
iness.com/click/29560330.279505/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYXFyLmNvbS9JbnNpZ2h0cy9QZXJ=
zcGVjdGl2ZXMvVGhlLUlsbGlxdWlkaXR5LURpc2NvdW50/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb3cb=
8e0a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" styl=
e=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-=
color: #ccc;"> The Illiquidity Discount</a>,=E2=80=9D in which he argues th=
at private equity is essentially in the business of selling illiquidity. If=
 you are a big institution and you buy stocks in public companies,=C2=A0the=
 stocks might go down, and you will be sad for various reasons. You might b=
e tempted to sell at the wrong time. You will have to report your results t=
o your stakeholders, and if the stocks went down those results will be bad =
and you will get yelled at or fired. Whereas if you put your money in a pri=
vate equity fund, it will buy whole public companies and take them private,=
 and then you won=E2=80=99t know what the stock price is and won=E2=80=99t =
be able to sell. The private equity fund will send you periodic reports abo=
ut the values of your investments, but those values won=E2=80=99t necessari=
ly move that much with public-market stock prices: The fund will base its v=
aluations on its estimates of long-term cash flows, and those will not chan=
ge from day to day. By=C2=A0<em>being=C2=A0</em>illiquid, the private equit=
y fund can=C2=A0<em>look=C2=A0</em>less volatile. Getting similar returns w=
ith less volatility is good; getting similar returns and=C2=A0<em>feeling=
=C2=A0</em>like you have less volatility also might be good.<a class=3D"foo=
tnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration:=
 none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; b=
order-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !importa=
nt; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a> Asness writes:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If people get that PE is truly vol=
atile but you just don=E2=80=99t see it, what=E2=80=99s all the excitement =
about? Well, big time multi-year illiquidity and its oft-accompanying prici=
ng opacity may actually be a feature not a bug! Liquid, accurately priced i=
nvestments let you know precisely how volatile they are and they smack you =
in the face with it.=C2=A0What if many investors actually realize that this=
 accurate and timely information will make them worse investors as they=E2=
=80=99ll use that liquidity to panic and redeem at the worst times? What if=
 illiquid, very infrequently and inaccurately priced investments made them =
better investors as essentially it allows them to ignore such investments g=
iven low measured volatility and very modest paper drawdowns? =E2=80=9CIgno=
re=E2=80=9D in this case equals =E2=80=9Cstick with through harrowing times=
 when you might sell if you had to face up to the full losses.=E2=80=9D Wha=
t if investors are simply smart enough to know that they can take on a lot =
more risk (true long-term risk) if it=E2=80=99s simply not shoved in their =
face every day (or multi-year period!)?=C2=A0</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One objection to this sort of financial produc=
t =E2=80=94=C2=A0illiquidity provision =E2=80=94=C2=A0is that it does not g=
enerate a lot of transactions. If you work at a bank and you think of a pro=
duct that will cause customers to trade bonds or houses or diamonds more of=
ten, then it is pretty easy to figure out how to make money from that produ=
ct. (Do the trades for the customers, and take a commission.) If you work a=
t a bank and you think of a product that will cause them to trade=C2=A0<em>=
less=C2=A0</em>often, it is harder. Basically you have to charge them a big=
ger fee for doing less work. =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99ll give you a bond fund th=
at offers instantaneous liquidity and transparent market prices and charge =
you five basis points a year, or we can give you a different fund that offe=
rs no liquidity and only updates prices when we feel like it, and that=E2=
=80=99s gonna be 200 basis points.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway here is a fun <a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29560330.279505/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9=
hcnRpY2xlcy9wdWJsaWMtcmVpdHMtYXJlLWRvd24tbm9udHJhZGVkLXJlaXRzLWFyZS11cC13aG=
ljaC1pcy1yaWdodC0xMTY2NzE3MTcxNz9tb2Q9aXRwX3dzaiZydT15YWhvbw/607f07ceef4b85=
24a319a23cBfe4e547c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;"> Wall Street Journal article about private RE=
ITs</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It has been a terrible year for many publicly =
traded real-estate investments as rising interest rates and falling propert=
y prices hit the market. The MSCI US REIT Index, which tracks publicly trad=
ed REITs, is down about 26% this year.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But it has been a strong year for a type of in=
vestment especially popular with individuals: nontraded real-estate investm=
ent trusts. Some of these funds have returned about 10%. The difference wor=
ries some investors=E2=80=94and it could cause losses for those who buy the=
se now thinking that nontraded REITs are immune to the market selloff.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CWith nontraded REITs increasing their=
 valuations while markets are punishing public REITs, I=E2=80=99d run for t=
he hills,=E2=80=9D said Allan Roth, founder of Wealth Logic LLC, a financia=
l planning firm based in Colorado Springs, Colo. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The valuations differ because public REITs are=
 valued at whatever their shares are trading for on the stock market. Nontr=
aded REITs are valued monthly by their sponsors working with independent ap=
praisers analyzing how much the commercial property they own is worth. =E2=
=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sponsors of nontraded REITs argue that their n=
et asset values continue to rise because they are still seeing strong cash =
flows. Some have taken steps to protect against a rise in interest rates; B=
lackstone says its rate hedges have added $4.4 billion this year to the val=
ue of its nontraded REIT. And the Blackstone and Starwood funds focus on so=
me of the strongest sectors such as apartments, where the housing market is=
 strong, and industrial properties that profit from the growth of e-commerc=
e. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sponsors note that the stock market is almost =
always more volatile than the value of the properties they own and that pub=
licly traded REITs began the year at excessive prices, a reason they have f=
allen so much. Blackstone executives have been buying shares of their fund =
recently.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you can buy a real estate investment that g=
oes up when public real estate investments goes down, that=E2=80=99s good! =
That=E2=80=99s valuable diversification! You are paying for illiquidity, an=
d getting what you paid for.</p>
