<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Libor</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At a high level, to be guilty of fraud, you ne=
ed to (1) say something false (2)=C2=A0know that it is false, or at least, =
have some sort of bad state of mind about what you are saying. (Not legal a=
dvice and not quite right, but a good rough intuition.)=C2=A0When people ge=
t prosecuted for fraud, often they will fight over both elements. =E2=80=9C=
Everything I said was more or less true, but if it wasn=E2=80=99t then that=
 was an honest mistake,=E2=80=9D they will say. But sometimes it is fairly =
obvious that what they said was=C2=A0<em>false</em>, and so all of the argu=
ments are over their state of mind: When they said these untrue things, wer=
e they trying to trick people by knowingly lying, or was it forgivable care=
lessness?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is rare, though, to have the opposite. It i=
s rare for someone to be accused of fraud and say =E2=80=9Cwell yes obvious=
ly I <em>intended=C2=A0</em>to lie, but what I said was=C2=A0<em>true</em>,=
 so it=E2=80=99s not fraud.=E2=80=9D It is not theoretically impossible, bu=
t it is weird. Usually when people try to lie they succeed, at least in the=
 narrow sense of =E2=80=9Cthey try to say something false and in fact say s=
omething false.=E2=80=9D On the rare occasions when they fail =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0when they try to lie and say something true instead =E2=80=94=C2=A0gener=
ally no one is tricked, and so there is no prosecution for fraud.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The state of fraud prosecutions for Libor, the=
 London interbank offered rate, is incredibly weird. Libor was a benchmark =
of banks=E2=80=99 borrowing costs that was used to set rates on trillions o=
f dollars of loans and derivatives. The way it was set was that the adminis=
trator of Libor would call up a bunch of banks every day and say =E2=80=9Ch=
ow much would you pay right now to borrow dollars for one month? Two months=
? Three months? What about yen?=E2=80=9D and so forth, through a range of c=
urrencies and tenors. And the banks would answer, and for each currency and=
 tenor the administrator would throw out the extreme answers and average th=
e rest, and that trimmed average would be two-month dollar Libor or whateve=
r. And occasionally a bank would get that call 30 seconds after it had nego=
tiated to borrow dollars for one month, and its Libor submitter =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0the person who answered the phone when the Libor administrator called=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0would confidently say =E2=80=9Cour one-month dollar borrowi=
ng cost is 2.7539%,=E2=80=9D and that was that. But most of the time the ba=
nk would not have taken out a two-month yen loan in the last hour, or the l=
ast day, or perhaps even the last week, and it would have no directly obser=
vable answer to the question. So it would estimate the answer. =E2=80=9CWe =
borrowed yen for one month yesterday at 0.25%, and since then rates seem to=
 have moved by about 0.02%, and the one-to-two-month curve is about 0.07%, =
so I=E2=80=99ll say 0.34%.=E2=80=9D And maybe that was actually the rate th=
at the bank would have paid to borrow yen for two months at the moment it a=
nswered the question, and maybe it wasn=E2=80=99t.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">These sorts of interpolations are not exactly =
rocket science, and the numbers the banks said were probably pretty close t=
o what their actual borrowing costs would be. But you could not say with mu=
ch confidence that they were exactly right.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then people at a bunch of banks got really=
 into doing fraud on Libor. The idea is that sometimes a derivatives trader=
=C2=A0had a billion dollars of derivatives that were indexed to three-month=
 dollar Libor, and if Libor was 0.01% higher he would make an extra $100,00=
0, and so he would call up his bank=E2=80=99s Libor submitter =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0and sometimes his buddies at other banks =E2=80=94=C2=A0to try to nudge =
Libor higher. And the submitter would be all ready to submit a Libor rate o=
f 2.75%, and the trader would instant message him and say =E2=80=9Chelp me =
out I need it higher,=E2=80=9D and the submitter would submit 2.76% instead=
.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And all of this would happen on permanently pr=
eserved electronic chats, and all of the chats were=C2=A0as <a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29560330.279505/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY=
mxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTUtMDQtMjMvZGV1dHNjaGUtYmFuay13=
YXMtZW1waGF0aWMtYWJvdXQtbWFuaXB1bGF0aW5nLWxpYm9yP2NtcGlkPUJCRDExMDEyMl9NT05=
FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPT=
IyMTEwMSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa63393ef"=
 itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color=
: #ccc;">  bad</a> as can <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
m/click/29560330.279505/aHR0cHM6Ly9ueW1hZy5jb20vaW50ZWxsaWdlbmNlci8yMDEzLzA=
yL2xpLWJyb3MtY29udGludWUtdG8tZS1tYWlsLWR1bWItdGhpbmdzLmh0bWw/607f07ceef4b85=
24a319a23cBa2c77279" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;"> be</a>. Basically the chats were like the tr=
aders saying =E2=80=9CI will pay you a bribe if you criminally manipulate L=
ibor by lying in your submission,=E2=80=9D and the submitters saying =E2=80=
=9Cokay I will do that because I am a dishonest liar, but I hope we do not =
get caught doing these blatant crimes,=E2=80=9D except with a lot more miss=
pellings. And so the banks got in trouble with regulators and quickly settl=
ed and paid billions of dollars of fines, and the individual traders who se=
nt those chats were prosecuted for fraud.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Most famously, Tom Hayes, a former UBS Group A=
G derivatives trader, was prosecuted in the UK for manipulating Libor; <a h=
ref=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29560330.279505/aHR0cH=
M6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTUtMDgtMDMvbGlib3ItZHJlY=
W1zLWVuZC1pbi1wcmlzb24tdGVybS1hcy10b20taGF5ZXMtbG9zZXMtbGFzdC1nYW1ibGU_Y21w=
aWQ9QkJEMTEwMTIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3N=
sZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIxMTAxJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8=
524a319a23cB1b72f0c8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">  he sat for</a> =E2=80=9C82 hours of intervi=
ews with investigators=E2=80=9D in which he said things like =E2=80=9CI pro=
bably deserve to be sitting here because, you know, I made concerted effort=
s to influence Libor,=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cultimately I was someone who wa=
s a serial offender.=E2=80=9D Unsurprisingly, he was convicted.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">He was also charged with crimes in the US, but=
 now <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29560330.2795=
05/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvY2JkMjFlOTAtNDIyMy00ZDU3LWIwODAtM2I1=
MWZkMmI0MGI0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6bd91a74" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" item=
scope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> those charges have=
 been thrown out</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A New York judge has thrown out criminal charg=
es against Tom Hayes, the former UBS and Citigroup trader who served more t=
han five years in prison in the UK for conspiring to manipulate the Libor b=
enchmark interest rate. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The decision to drop US charges against Hayes =
follows an appeals court ruling in a separate US case, which overturned the=
 Libor-rigging convictions of two former Deutsche Bank traders. That ruling=
 found the government had =E2=80=9Cfailed to show that any of the trader-in=
fluenced submissions were false, fraudulent or misleading=E2=80=9D.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/29560330.279505/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL=
2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDEtMzEvbGlib3Itd2FzLW1hZGUtdXAtYW55d2F5P2NtcGlkPUJCRDEx=
MDEyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV=
0bV90ZXJtPTIyMTEwMSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23=
cB47999e5c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;">  talked about that earlier ruling in January</a>. The =
problem=C2=A0with the Libor prosecutions=C2=A0is that nobody ever proved th=
at the Libor submissions were <em>wrong</em>. Obviously the traders and sub=
mitters were=C2=A0<em>trying=C2=A0</em>to lie: The chats are terrible and s=
how their state of mind pretty clearly, and anyway Hayes spent hours confes=
sing to manipulating Libor. But there is no proof that they=C2=A0<em>succee=
ded=C2=A0</em>in lying: If a Libor submitter thought that his bank could bo=
rrow at 2.75%, and instead told the Libor administrator that it could borro=
w at 2.76%, either number might have been right! The appeals court pointed =
out that banks regularly borrowed different amounts of money from different=
 counterparties at different rates at around the same time; it simply is no=
t true that there was One Correct Rate that a bank would have paid to borro=
w money on any particular day. There is probably some range, and if you pic=
k a number in the range you are telling the truth, even if you are consciou=
sly <em>trying=C2=A0</em>to pick the wrong number.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">More to the point, it is very hard to=C2=A0<em=
>prove=C2=A0</em>that you are lying. I mean, if you borrowed a lot of dolla=
rs for three months at 2.75% right before the Libor administrators called, =
and then borrowed more at 2.75% right after, and you said =E2=80=9C2.76%=E2=
=80=9D when they called and asked for your three-month dollar borrowing rat=
e, then that seems bad. But that is probably pretty rare, and ordinarily th=
ere will be some room for judgment. And the burden of proof is on the prose=
cution: They need to prove that your Libor submission was false, rather tha=
n you proving that it was true. That will generally be hard, and in any cas=
e US prosecutors never even tried. They looked at all those chats, all thos=
e confessions of guilt, and figured that they were good enough to prove tha=
t the traders were lying. But they never quite proved that they weren=E2=80=
=99t also telling the truth.</p>
